 Nairobi, April 7 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Kenya's central bank governor echoed the government's forecast of 4.5 to 6.0 percent economic growth in 2008 on Monday and said the bank did not intend to act to curb soaring inflation. Finance Minister Amos Kimunya issued his second warning about the country's expected growth last week, saying it could fall as low as 4.0-4.5 percent though he still hoped for 6 percent after post-election violence hurt key economic sectors. "The worst case scenario is 4.5 percent, the best case scenario is 6 percent," Central Bank Governor Njuguna Ndung'u told reporters. "The way the economy is going and given the vibrancy in the market, we may get to the neighbourhood of 6 percent." Kenya's economy grew by an estimated 6.9 percent last year. Ndung'u also said the bank did not plan to act on rising inflation which was a supply side problem. Overall annual inflation rose to 21.8 percent in March from 19.1 percent in February due to a sharp rise in food prices. Underlying inflation, which excludes food prices, rose to 9.8 percent in March from 9.3 percent in February. "It is a supply side problem. It is not a monetary side problem, so you cannot take action on supply side because they are seasonal," Ndung'u added. He said market players should look at core inflation figures for a snapshot of the fundamentals driving the economy, because the overall rate was affected by seasonal food supplies and political shocks. Kenya's economic pillars, including tourism, agriculture and transport, are still recovering from the damage caused by post-election unrest that killed more than 1,200 people and displaced another 300,000. Last week, the agriculture ministry said fertiliser prices have shot up, fuelling fears of food shortages later this ye
